<!-- CONTENT -->
<div class="page-layout">
<div>

  <!-- 01 — CONTEXT -->
  <div class="section" id="context">
    <div class="section-num">01 — Context</div>
    <h2>The business problem this project solves</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      Most finance portfolios show either a spreadsheet model or a dashboard — rarely both,
      and almost never the data pipeline that connects them. This project builds the full stack:
      a <strong>SQLite operational database</strong> that feeds a <strong>three-statement Excel model</strong>
      that feeds a <strong>Power BI executive dashboard</strong>.
    </p>
    <p class="prose">
      NorthStar SaaS is a fictional B2B software company with three subscription tiers,
      500 customers across seven countries, and a deliberate three-act financial narrative:
      strong growth in 2022, market pressure in 2023, and recovery in 2024.
      The dataset was designed to tell a story that requires explanation —
      not a straight line up and to the right.
    </p>
    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p><strong>The most important skill in FP&A is not building models — it is knowing
      what story the numbers are telling</strong> and being able to explain why they changed.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Architecture -->
    <div class="arch">
      <div class="arch-box">
        <div class="arch-box-title">SQL</div>
        <div class="arch-box-sub">SQLite database<br/>4 tables · 40K rows<br/>Python-generated</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="arch-box">
        <div class="arch-box-title">Excel</div>
        <div class="arch-box-sub">3-statement model<br/>P&L · Balance · CF<br/>Scenario toggle</div>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="arch-box">
        <div class="arch-box-title">Power BI</div>
        <div class="arch-box-sub">Executive dashboard<br/>DAX measures<br/>5 KPI cards</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 02 — DATABASE -->
  <div class="section" id="database">
    <div class="section-num">02 — SQL Database</div>
    <h2>Building the source of truth</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      The database was built in SQLite using Python — four tables that mirror how a real
      SaaS finance team structures its data warehouse. Each table has a specific role
      in the financial model.
    </p>

    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Table</th><th>Rows</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="val-hi">customers</td><td>500</td><td>Master customer list — plan, country, acquisition date, CSM owner</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="val-hi">subscriptions</td><td>40,506</td><td>One row per customer per active month — MRR and status (new, active, expansion, contraction, churned)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="val-hi">expenses</td><td>2,160</td><td>Monthly operating costs by category — COGS, S&M, R&D, G&A</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="val-hi">headcount</td><td>864</td><td>Monthly headcount and fully-loaded salary cost by department</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p class="prose">
      The <strong>subscriptions table is the financial core</strong> of the model. Each row
      captures a customer's status in a given month — and the combination of all rows
      produces the MRR waterfall that drives every downstream calculation.
      Churn rates were deliberately varied by year to create a non-trivial dataset:
      1.8% monthly in 2022, 4.2% in 2023, and 2.4% in 2024.
    </p>

    <div class="insight">
      <span class="insight-icon">SQL</span>
      <p class="insight-text">
        The most complex query in the project was the <strong>NRR calculation</strong> —
        a self-join that compares each customer's MRR against their own MRR exactly
        12 months prior, excluding new customers entirely. This required a CTE combined
        with a DATE offset join: <em>ON c.month = DATE(t.month, '+12 months')</em>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="prose">Five analytical views were exported as CSVs and loaded into Excel:</p>
    <div class="pipeline">
      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <span class="pipeline-num">01</span>
        <div class="pipeline-content">
          <div class="pipeline-title">mrr_summary — monthly MRR, active customers, avg MRR per customer</div>
          <div class="pipeline-desc">Base revenue view. Foundation for the P&L revenue block.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <span class="pipeline-num">02</span>
        <div class="pipeline-content">
          <div class="pipeline-title">mrr_movement — new, expansion, contraction, churned MRR by month</div>
          <div class="pipeline-desc">MRR waterfall decomposition. Powers the movement chart in Power BI.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <span class="pipeline-num">03</span>
        <div class="pipeline-content">
          <div class="pipeline-title">churn_rate — monthly churn rate percentage</div>
          <div class="pipeline-desc">Retention health metric. Confirms the 2023 stress narrative.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <span class="pipeline-num">04</span>
        <div class="pipeline-content">
          <div class="pipeline-title">nrr — net revenue retention by month (Jan 2023 onward)</div>
          <div class="pipeline-desc">Requires 12 months of history — available from Jan 2023.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <span class="pipeline-num">05</span>
        <div class="pipeline-content">
          <div class="pipeline-title">ltv_cac — lifetime value and CAC ratio by plan</div>
          <div class="pipeline-desc">Unit economics by segment. Enterprise LTV/CAC: 35x.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 03 — EXCEL MODEL -->
  <div class="section" id="excel">
    <div class="section-num">03 — Excel Financial Model</div>
    <h2>Three-statement model with scenario analysis</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      The Excel model follows a strict one-directional data flow across four tabs —
      a standard in investment banking and FP&A that prevents circular references
      and makes the model auditable.
    </p>

    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Tab</th><th>Role</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="val-hi">DATA</td><td>Raw CSV imports — never edited directly. Single source of truth.</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="val-hi">ASSUMPTIONS</td><td>All editable inputs: pricing, churn rates, CAC, salaries, scenario toggle.</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="val-hi">P&L</td><td>36-month income statement with KPI block. All formulas reference ASSUMPTIONS.</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="val-hi">DASHBOARD</td><td>Charts and summary table for presentation.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p class="prose">
      The scenario toggle in ASSUMPTIONS drives two multipliers — Revenue and Cost —
      that cascade through every formula in the P&L via a single cell reference.
      Switching from Base to Bull increases revenue by 15% and costs by 5% across
      all 36 months simultaneously.
    </p>

    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p>The key design principle: <strong>every number that could change lives in ASSUMPTIONS.
      No hardcoded values inside formulas.</strong> This is what makes a model
      maintainable and trustworthy in a real finance team.</p>
    </div>

    <p class="prose">Key P&L findings across the three scenarios:</p>

    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Jan 2022</th><th>Jan 2023</th><th>Dec 2024</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Total MRR</td><td>$693</td><td>$279,806</td><td>$528,586</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="val-hi">EBITDA</td><td class="val-neg">$(23,649)</td><td class="val-pos">$50,162</td><td class="val-pos">$94,762</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Gross Margin</td><td>81.7%</td><td>81.7%</td><td>81.7%</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="val-hi">Churn Rate</td><td class="val-dim">0.00%</td><td class="val-neg">4.58%</td><td class="val-pos">2.05%</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="val-hi">NRR</td><td class="val-dim">—</td><td>100.0%</td><td class="val-pos">118.0%</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="insight">
      <span class="insight-icon">Note</span>
      <p class="insight-text">
        <strong>Jan 2022 shows negative EBITDA of $(23,649)</strong> — a deliberate model decision.
        Fixed cost floors were added to S&M ($15K minimum) and G&A ($8K minimum) using
        MAX() functions, ensuring costs reflect real pre-revenue investment rather than
        scaling to zero with MRR.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 04 — POWER BI -->
  <div class="section" id="powerbi">
    <div class="section-num">04 — Power BI Dashboard</div>
    <h2>Translating the model into executive communication</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      The dashboard was built directly on top of the Excel analytical views,
      with DAX measures handling all dynamic calculations. The design
      prioritizes the narrative over decoration — every visual answers
      a specific question a CFO or investor would ask.
    </p>

    <!-- Dashboard preview (SVG representation) -->
    <div class="dashboard-preview">
      <!-- KPI row -->
      <div class="kpi-row">
        <div class="kpi-box"><div class="kpi-num">$726,085</div><div class="kpi-lbl">Latest MRR</div></div>
        <div class="kpi-box"><div class="kpi-num">$8,713,023</div><div class="kpi-lbl">ARR</div></div>
