  <!-- 05 — FINDINGS -->
  <div class="section" id="findings">
    <div class="section-num">05 — Key Findings</div>
    <h2>What the data demonstrated</h2>
    <div class="findings">
      <div class="finding">
        <div class="finding-stat">111.6%</div>
        <div class="finding-title">Final NRR</div>
        <p class="finding-body">NorthStar's existing customer base grew 11.6% annually without a single new acquisition. Expansion MRR consistently outpaced churn MRR from mid-2022 onward.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding">
        <div class="finding-stat">4.58%</div>
        <div class="finding-title">Peak churn — Jan 2023</div>
        <p class="finding-body">The 2023 stress year is clearly visible in the data. Churn more than doubled from the 2022 baseline, yet total MRR continued growing — evidence that new and expansion MRR absorbed the losses.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding">
        <div class="finding-stat">$(23K)</div>
        <div class="finding-title">EBITDA in Month 1</div>
        <p class="finding-body">Negative EBITDA in January 2022 reflects realistic pre-revenue investment. Fixed cost floors in S&M and G&A prevent the model from showing false profitability at near-zero revenue.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding">
        <div class="finding-stat">35x</div>
        <div class="finding-title">Enterprise LTV/CAC</div>
        <p class="finding-body">Enterprise customers generate 35x their acquisition cost over their lifetime. Even with simplified CAC assumptions, the unit economics confirm Enterprise as the most capital-efficient segment.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 06 — LIMITATIONS -->
  <div class="section" id="limitations">
    <div class="section-num">06 — Limitations & Extensions</div>
    <h2>What this model does not do</h2>
    <ul class="limit-list">
      <li>
        <span class="limit-tag">Balance Sheet</span>
        <span class="limit-text">The model covers P&L only. A complete 3-statement model would add a Balance Sheet (cash, deferred revenue, equity) and Cash Flow Statement linked to P&L line items.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="limit-tag">Deferred Revenue</span>
        <span class="limit-text"><strong>Annual prepayments are not modeled.</strong> In a real SaaS model, customers who pay annually create a deferred revenue liability that unwinds monthly — this affects the Balance Sheet and Cash Flow significantly.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="limit-tag">Cohort Analysis</span>
        <span class="limit-text">Churn rate is calculated at the aggregate level. A production model would track retention by acquisition cohort — revealing whether newer customers churn faster or slower than older ones.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="limit-tag">CAC Derivation</span>
        <span class="limit-text">CAC is currently a fixed benchmark assumption. In a rigorous model it would be calculated dynamically as <strong>total S&M spend divided by new customers acquired</strong> — pulling directly from the expenses table.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="limit-tag">Next Step</span>
        <span class="limit-text"><strong>Module 2:</strong> Add Balance Sheet and Cash Flow Statement to complete the three-statement model, with deferred revenue waterfall and operating cash conversion metrics.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

